The paper proposes a privacy protocol for distributed consensus algorithms, which is a topic in distributed computing (cs.DC). The protocol is designed to protect against colluding agents, which is a security concern and falls under the category of cryptography and security (cs.CR). The paper also deals with the concept of statistical privacy, which is a topic in information theory (cs.IT). The proposed protocol involves the use of bounds on real-valued inputs, which is a topic in machine learning and optimization (cs.LG). Finally, the paper mentions applications in distributed control and state estimation, which is a topic in systems and control (cs.SY).
